<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-683-807  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 683 807.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Nov 29 1990 n1241 p22(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Don't be lulled into a false sense of security. (the UK ComputerMisuse Bill and the Data Protection Act place greater securityobligations on information technology management)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pearson, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The UK's Computer Misuse Bill and Data Protection Act placegreater legal and professional responsibilities on informationtechnology (IT) managers.andP;  Computer misuse costs the UK 1 billionpounds sterling annually, with the UK Department of Trade alonerecording 270 computer crime cases in the last five years.andP;  Thegrowth in business use of IT, particularly networking, providesnew opportunities for criminal misuse of computers andinformation.andP;  The most susceptible technologies aremicrocomputers, particularly in local area networks, because ITmanagement tends to ignore their security.andP;  Consequently, thereare more opportunities to misuse the shared resources, accessconfidential data and infect the systems with viruses.andP;  The DataProtection Act creates new laws to control such offenses but itwill take better IT management to enforce security in the firstplace.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United KingdomLegislationImpact AnalysisSecurityManagement of EDPFailurePerformance ImprovementRequirements AnalysisData Security.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>